Feature: bc-container launch --orchestrator fabro replaces the engage tier with an ephemeral in-container fabro server that runs the loop def, while --orchestrator tmux (the default) leaves the existing tmux engage unchanged

  SLICE 4 of the fabro launch path (epic lead-kqgp, under lead-6k1r; S4 work_id
  lead-cadr, target shopsystem-bc-launcher, assign_scenarios). S1 (scenario 73,
  @scenario_hash:a3512aedb8763150) baked the fabro substrate; S2 (scenario 75,
  @scenario_hash:2dfefe2ba81e418d) shipped+placed the self-contained fabro def at
  "/workspace/.fabro/"; S3 (scenario 76, @scenario_hash:8b5a1b9e5499293b) started
  the anthropic-oauth-shim and pointed fabro's anthropic "base_url" at it, and
  introduced an off-by-default "--fabro-path" flag gating that block. Substrate +
  def + credential bridge make the loop RUNNABLE in-container; this slice pins the
  last step — the launcher ENGAGING that loop on the fabro path in place of tmux.

  WHAT S4 PINS. On the fabro orchestrator launch path, AFTER the SAME idempotent
  readiness barrier passes (scenario 34, composing the messaging DB and the
  agent-vault broker; ADR-050 D4), the launcher (a) STARTS the ephemeral
  in-container fabro server — "provider=local", foreground, no web UI, bound to a
  local 127.0.0.1 socket ("fabro server start --foreground --no-web"), so the loop
  runs headless inside the one bc-base container — and (b) invokes "fabro run
  workflow.fabro -I BC_NAME=<bc> -I WORK_ID=<id>" against it as the ENGAGE step,
  carrying BC_NAME/WORK_ID into the run via the def's "[run.environment.env]" so
  the ADR-051 Implementer->Reviewer loop def (scenario 75) is the agent loop that
  engages, and (c) runs NO tmux "agent" send-keys session and NO "claude" engage on
  that path. This is the ENGAGE-TIER-ONLY REPLACEMENT (ADR-050 D3): the container,
  credential-proxy, postgres DSN and shop-msg mailbox surfaces are unchanged
  (ADR-050 D1/D2); only the engage tier differs. It REPRODUCES the graduated
  fabro-orchestration/01 launch-parity boot (@scenario_hash:1aeace4c593ab14f) VIA
  THE REAL "bc-container launch" path rather than the hand-provisioned spike boot.

  CANONICAL CLI (--orchestrator {tmux|fabro}, default tmux). This slice establishes
  the pinned launch surface "bc-container launch <bc> --orchestrator {tmux|fabro}",
  with "tmux" the default. It reconciles/renames S3's off-by-default "--fabro-path"
  onto "--orchestrator fabro" (S3's flag may remain only as a hidden alias). The
  DEFAULT path — no flag, or "--orchestrator tmux" — is UNCHANGED: the existing
  tmux "agent" send-keys engage (scenario 04, @scenario_hash:04236074a60ffcd7)
  fires after the barrier exactly as before, and NO fabro server is started and NO
  "fabro run" is issued. This is the ADR-050 launch-parity invariant: fabro is a
  drop-in alternate PATH, not a new default.

  WHAT THE BC BUILDS AND CHECKS STRUCTURALLY. The bc-launcher build host lacks a
  live docker daemon, a running fabro server, and a reachable agent-vault, so the
  LIVE fabro-server boot (the graph actually running a BC loop) is deliberately NOT
  this scenario's in-container checkable core — it is the LEAD end-to-end check.
  What the BC builds and verifies structurally is the ENGAGE STEP the launcher
  ISSUES on each path, all observable without a live daemon: on "--orchestrator
  fabro" the launcher issues the exact "fabro server start --foreground --no-web"
  and "fabro run workflow.fabro -I BC_NAME=<bc> -I WORK_ID=<id>" argv (gated on the
  fabro path) and issues no tmux engage; on the default the launcher issues the
  tmux engage and no fabro argv. The behavior pinned is the REAL launcher-issued
  engage commands; only their at-the-wire consummation folds into the lead E2E.

  LAUNCH PARITY (ADR-050) / SCOPE. fabro runs in-container only (provider=local,
  127.0.0.1). This changes nothing about the container/credential/network tiers or
  the shop-msg mailbox (ADR-050 D1/D2); it REPLACES only the engage tier on the
  fabro path (D3) and leaves the tmux default fully intact. Distinct from, and not
  a duplicate of: scenario 73 (substrate baked), scenario 75 (def present +
  validate), scenario 76 (shim started + base_url wired), scenario 34 (the barrier
  itself), and fabro-orchestration/01 (the parity boot as a lead-process contract —
  THIS pins the bc-launcher launcher-issued half). (Targets shopsystem-bc-launcher
  / bc-base, owned per ADR-021.)

  @scenario_hash:68e14cdcd8b7c145
  Scenario: bc-container launch --orchestrator fabro starts the ephemeral in-container fabro server and runs the loop def as the engage step, running no tmux engage on that path
    Given the shopsystem-bc-launcher BC is installed
    And bc-container launch is run for BC name "shopsystem-messaging" with work id "lead-cadr" on the fabro orchestrator launch path selected by "--orchestrator fabro"
    And the container "bc-shopsystem-messaging" is running on the pinned bc-base image carrying the self-contained fabro def at "/workspace/.fabro/" (scenario 75, @scenario_hash:2dfefe2ba81e418d) with the started anthropic-oauth-shim and fabro's anthropic "base_url" wired to it (scenario 76, @scenario_hash:8b5a1b9e5499293b)
    And the launcher's idempotent readiness barrier composing the messaging DB and the agent-vault broker has passed (scenario 34)
    When the engage step the launcher issues on the fabro orchestrator path is inspected structurally, without a live docker daemon, a running fabro server, or a reachable agent-vault
    Then AFTER the readiness barrier passes the launcher starts an ephemeral in-container fabro server running "provider=local" in the foreground with no web UI bound to a local 127.0.0.1 socket, issuing the argv "fabro server start --foreground --no-web", so the loop runs headless inside the one bc-base container and nothing is orchestrated outside it
    And the launcher invokes "fabro run workflow.fabro -I BC_NAME=shopsystem-messaging -I WORK_ID=lead-cadr" against that server as the engage step, carrying BC_NAME and WORK_ID into the run via the def's "[run.environment.env]", so the ADR-051 Implementer->Reviewer loop def (scenario 75) is the agent loop that engages
    And no tmux "agent" send-keys session and no "claude" engage is started on this path, the engage tier being REPLACED by the fabro run-graph entry rather than added alongside it (ADR-050 D3), reproducing fabro-orchestration/01 (@scenario_hash:1aeace4c593ab14f) via the real bc-container launch path
    And the container, credential-proxy, postgres DSN and shop-msg mailbox surfaces are unchanged from the tmux path, only the engage tier differing (ADR-050 D1/D2 launch parity)

  @scenario_hash:ee8f4803eb5342f0
  Scenario: bc-container launch defaults --orchestrator to tmux and leaves the existing tmux engage unchanged, starting no fabro server and issuing no fabro run
    Given the shopsystem-bc-launcher BC is installed
    And bc-container launch is run for BC name "shopsystem-messaging" with no "--orchestrator" flag supplied
    And the launcher's idempotent readiness barrier has passed (scenario 34)
    When the engage step the launcher issues is inspected structurally, without a live docker daemon or a running fabro server
    Then the orchestrator defaults to "tmux", the canonical launch surface being "bc-container launch <bc> --orchestrator {tmux|fabro}" with "tmux" the default, superseding S3's off-by-default "--fabro-path" flag which may remain only as a hidden alias
    And AFTER the readiness barrier passes the launcher engages via the existing tmux "agent" send-keys path exactly as scenario 04 (@scenario_hash:04236074a60ffcd7) pins, unchanged
    And the launcher starts no ephemeral fabro server and issues no "fabro run" on this default path, so the fabro engage replacement is confined to "--orchestrator fabro" (ADR-050 D1 tmux-default launch parity preserved)
